<!-- PLEASE ADD CATEGORIES AND INTERWIKIS AT THE BOTTOM OF THIS PAGE. -->
===Usage===
This template rounds {{{1}}} to {{{2}}} decimal places (goes the other way for negatives) and includes trailing zeros.  Scientific notation is used for numbers greater than or equal to 1{{e|9}}, or less than 1{{e|−4}}.

Compare:
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|2.0004|3}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|2.0004|3}}
**whereas <tt><nowiki>{{#expr:2.0004 round 3}}</nowiki></tt> → {{#expr:2.0004 round 3}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|0.000020004|7}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|0.000020004|7}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|0|8}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|0|8}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|154268|-3}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|154268|-3}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|1200004|-1}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|1200004|-1}}
**whereas <tt><nowiki>{{#expr:1200004round-1}}</nowiki></tt> → {{#expr:1200004round-1}}, even though <tt><nowiki>{{#expr:1300004round-1}}</nowiki></tt> → {{#expr:1300004round-1}} (see [[m:Help:Format produced by expr]]) 
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|1300004|-1}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|1300004|-1}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|4.1e6|9}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|4.1e6|9}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|4.1e6|10}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|4.1e6|10}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|1542689271|-7}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|1542689271|-7}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|1542689271|2}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|1542689271|2}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|7e9|-9}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|7e9|-9}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|-123|1}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|-123|1}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|-1200007|-2}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|-1200007|-2}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|-1234567899|-7}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|-1234567899|-7}}

As with #expr, the total number of significant digits is not more than 14:
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|1234567890.123456789|10}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|1234567890.123456789|10}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|123456789.0123456789|10}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|123456789.0123456789|10}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|.0001234567890123456789|20}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd|.0001234567890123456789|20}}

===Internal details===
The template uses three subtemplates:
*{{tl|rnd/-}} — for trailing zeros
*{{tl|rnd/e+}} — for scientific notation for numbers greater than or equal to 10<sup>9</sup> or less than or equal to −10<sup>9</sup>
*{{tl|rnd/e−}} — for scientific notation for numbers greater than −10<sup>−4</sup> and less than 10<sup>−4</sup> but not equal to zero
<includeonly><!--
++++ PLEASE ADD CATEGORIES AND INTERWIKIS BELOW THIS LINE, THANK YOU. -->
[[Category:Mathematical function templates|{{PAGENAME}}]]
</includeonly>

{{Documentation subpage}} This subtemplate of {{tl|rnd}} adds trailing zeros. It takes two parameters. #the number to be displayed #the number of significant figures to be displayed after the decimal point
*<tt><nowiki>{{rnd/-|2|3}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd/-|2|3}} *<tt><nowiki>{{rnd/-|1E+5|3}}</nowiki></tt> → {{rnd/-|1E+5|3}}
It's used by {{tl|rnd}}. *"<tt><nowiki>{{#expr:2.0004 round 3}}</nowiki></tt>" gives "{{#expr:2.0004 round 3}}" *"<tt><nowiki>{{rnd|2.0004|3}}</nowiki></tt>" gives "{{rnd|2.0004|3}}" <includeonly> [[Category:Template subpages|{{PAGENAME}}]] </includeonly>

{{Documentation subpage}}

===Usage===
This template calculates the (decimal) [[w:order of magnitude|order of magnitude]] of numbers within the ranges 10<sup>300</sup> to 10<sup>−300</sup> and −10<sup>−300</sup> to −10<sup>300</sup>.

The acceptable input and the output produced are optimized for use in other templates. 
*The hyphen (not a true minus sign) is used for negative numbers.
*No separator is used for thousands. 
*The template gives 0 for 0.  Although, strictly speaking, this is mathematically incorrect it has been designed this way so as to be more useful in other templates.  An important example of this is that when used by {{tl|convert}} 0&nbsp;°C or 0&nbsp;°F is considered to be on the same order of magnitude as ±1&nbsp;°C or ±1&nbsp;°F respectively.

===Examples===
*<tt><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude|123400}}</nowiki></tt> → {{Order of magnitude|123400}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude|12340}}</nowiki></tt> → {{Order of magnitude|12340}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude|1234}}</nowiki></tt> → {{Order of magnitude|1234}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude|123.4}}</nowiki></tt> → {{Order of magnitude|123.4}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude|12.34}}</nowiki></tt> → {{Order of magnitude|12.34}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude|1.234}}</nowiki></tt> → {{Order of magnitude|1.234}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude|.1234}}</nowiki></tt> → {{Order of magnitude|.1234}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude|.01234}}</nowiki></tt> → {{Order of magnitude|.01234}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude|0}}</nowiki></tt> → {{Order of magnitude|0}}
*<tt><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude}}</nowiki></tt> → {{Order of magnitude}}

===Incorrect usage===
The input must be an unformatted number, or the template will emit errors:
*<code><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude|}}</nowiki></code> → <strong class="error">Expression error: Unexpected = operator</strong>
*<code><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude|123,400}}</nowiki></code> → <strong class="error">Expression error: Unrecognised punctuation character ","</strong>
*<code><nowiki>{{Order of magnitude|foo}}</nowiki></code> → <strong class="error">Expression error: Unrecognised word "foo"</strong>
